## Isotropy Subgroups

Let $X$ be a $G$-set. Let $x \in X$ and $g \in G$. It will be important to know when $g x=x$. We let

$$
X_{g}=\{x \in X \mid g x=x\} \quad \text { and } \quad G_{x}=\{g \in G \mid g x=x\} \text {. }
$$

16.11 Example For the $D_{4}$-set $X$ in Example 16.8, we have

$$
X_{\rho_{0}}=X, \quad X_{\rho_{1}}=\{C\}, \quad X_{\mu_{1}}=\left\{s_{1}, s_{3}, m_{1}, m_{2}, C, P_{1}, P_{3}\right\}
$$

Also, with $G=D_{4}$,

$$
G_{1}=\left\{\rho_{0}, \delta_{2}\right\}, \quad G_{s_{3}}=\left\{\rho_{0}, \mu_{1}\right\}, \quad G_{d_{1}}=\left\{\rho_{0}, \rho_{2}, \delta_{1}, \delta_{2}\right\} .
$$

We leave the computation of the other $X_{\sigma}$ and $G_{x}$ to Exercises 1 and 2.

Note that the subsets $G_{x}$ given in the preceding example were, in each case, subgroups of $G$. This is true in general.

16.12 Theorem Let $X$ be a $G$-set. Then $G_{x}$ is a subgroup of $G$ for each $x \in X$.

Proof Let $x \in X$ and let $g_{1}, g_{2} \in G_{x}$. Then $g_{1} x=x$ and $g_{2} x=x$. Consequently, $\left(g_{1} g_{2}\right) x=$ $g_{1}\left(g_{2} x\right)=g_{1} x=x$, so $g_{1} g_{2} \in G_{x}$, and $G_{x}$ is closed under the induced operation of $G$. Of course $e x=x$, so $e \in G_{x}$. If $g \in G_{x}$, then $g x=x$, so $x=e x=\left(g^{-1} g\right) x=g^{-1}(g x)=$ $g^{-1} x$, and consequently $g^{-1} \in G_{x}$. Thus $G_{x}$ is a subgroup of $G$.

16.13 Definition Let $X$ be a $G$-set and let $x \in X$. The subgroup $G_{x}$ is the isotropy subgroup of $x$.

## Orbits

For the $D_{4}$-set $X$ of Example 16.8 with action table in Table 16.10, the elements in the subset $\{1,2,3,4\}$ are carried into elements of this same subset under action by $D_{4}$. Furthermore, each of the elements $1,2,3$, and 4 is carried into all the other elements of the subset by the various elements of $D_{4}$. We proceed to show that every $G$-set $X$ can be partitioned into subsets of this type.

16.14 Theorem Let $X$ be a $G$-set. For $x_{1}, x_{2} \in X$, let $x_{1} \sim x_{2}$ if and only if there exists $g \in G$ such that $g x_{1}=x_{2}$. Then $\sim$ is an equivalence relation on $X$.

Proof For each $x \in X$, we have $e x=x$, so $x \sim x$ and $\sim$ is reflexive.

Suppose $x_{1} \sim x_{2}$, so $g x_{1}=x_{2}$ for some $g \in G$. Then $g^{-1} x_{2}=g^{-1}\left(g x_{1}\right)=$ $\left(g^{-1} g\right) x_{1}=e x_{1}=x_{1}$, so $x_{2} \sim x_{1}$, and $\sim$ is symmetric.

Finally, if $x_{1} \sim x_{2}$ and $x_{2} \sim x_{3}$, then $g_{1} x_{1}=x_{2}$ and $g_{2} x_{2}=x_{3}$ for some $g_{1}, g_{2} \in G$. Then $\left(g_{2} g_{1}\right) x_{1}=g_{2}\left(g_{1} x_{1}\right)=g_{2} x_{2}=x_{3}$, so $x_{1} \sim x_{3}$ and $\sim$ is transitive.

16.15 Definition Let $X$ be a $G$-set. Each cell in the partition of the equivalence relation described in Theorem 16.14 is an orbit in $X$ under $G$. If $x \in X$, the cell containing $x$ is the orbit of $x$. We let this cell be $G x$.

The relationship between the orbits in $X$ and the group structure of $G$ lies at the heart of the applications that appear in Section 17. The following theorem gives this relationship. Recall that for a set $X$, we use $|X|$ for the number of elements in $X$, and $(G: H)$ is the index of a subgroup $H$ in a group $G$.

16.16 Theorem Let $X$ be a $G$-set and let $x \in X$. Then $|G x|=\left(G: G_{x}\right)$. If $|G|$ is finite, then $|G x|$ is a divisor of $|G|$.

Proof We define a one-to-one map $\psi$ from $G x$ onto the collection of left cosets of $G_{x}$ in $G$. Let $x_{1} \in G x$. Then there exists $g_{1} \in G$ such that $g_{1} x=x_{1}$. We define $\psi\left(x_{1}\right)$ to be the left coset $g_{1} G_{x}$ of $G_{x}$. We must show that this map $\psi$ is well defined, independent of the choice of $g_{1} \in G$ such that $g_{1} x=x_{1}$. Suppose also that $g_{1}{ }^{\prime} x=x_{1}$. Then, $g_{1} x=g_{1}{ }^{\prime} x$, so $g_{1}^{-1}\left(g_{1} x\right)=g_{1}^{-1}\left(g_{1}^{\prime} x\right)$, from which we deduce $x=\left(g_{1}^{-1} g_{1}{ }^{\prime}\right) x$. Therefore $g_{1}^{-1} g_{1}{ }^{\prime} \in G_{x}$, so $g_{1}{ }^{\prime} \in g_{1} G_{x}$, and $g_{1} G_{x}=g_{1}{ }^{\prime} G_{x}$. Thus the map $\psi$ is well defined.

To show the map $\psi$ is one to one, suppose $x_{1}, x_{2} \in G x$, and $\psi\left(x_{1}\right)=\psi\left(x_{2}\right)$. Then there exist $g_{1}, g_{2} \in G$ such that $x_{1}=g_{1} x, x_{2}=g_{2} x$, and $g_{2} \in g_{1} G_{x}$. Then $g_{2}=g_{1} g$ for some $g \in G_{x}$, so $x_{2}=g_{2} x=g_{1}(g x)=g_{1} x=x_{1}$. Thus $\psi$ is one to one.

Finally, we show that each left coset of $G_{x}$ in $G$ is of the form $\psi\left(x_{1}\right)$ for some $x_{1} \in G x$. Let $g_{1} G_{x}$ be a left coset. Then if $g_{1} x=x_{1}$, we have $g_{1} G_{x}=\psi\left(x_{1}\right)$. Thus $\psi$ maps $G x$ one to one onto the collection of left cosets so $|G x|=\left(G: G_{x}\right)$.

If $|G|$ is finite, then the equation $|G|=\left|G_{x}\right|\left(G: G_{x}\right)$ shows that $|G x|=\left(G: G_{x}\right)$ is a divisor of $|G|$.

16.17 Example Let $X$ be the $D_{4}$-set in Example 16.8, with action table given by Table 16.10. With $G=D_{4}$, we have $G 1=\{1,2,3,4\}$ and $G_{1}=\left\{\rho_{0}, \delta_{2}\right\}$. Since $|G|=8$, we have $|G 1|=$ $\left(G: G_{1}\right)=4$.

We should remember not only the cardinality equation in Theorem 16.16 but also that the elements of $G$ carrying $x$ into $g_{1} x$ are precisely the elements of the left coset $g_{1} G_{x}$. Namely, if $g \in G_{x}$, then $\left(g_{1} g\right) x=g_{1}(g x)=g_{1} x$. On the other hand, if $g_{2} x=g_{1} x$, then $g_{1}^{-1}\left(g_{2} x\right)=x$ so $\left(g_{1}^{-1} g_{2}\right) x=x$. Thus $g_{1}^{-1} g_{2} \in G_{x}$ so $g_{2} \in g_{1} G_{x}$.

