## SECTION 48 AUTOMORPHISMS OF FIELDS

## The Conjugation Isomorphisms of Algebraic Field Theory

Let $F$ be a field, and let $\bar{F}$ be an algebraic closure of $F$, that is, an algebraic extension of $F$ that is algebraically closed. Such a field $\bar{F}$ exists, by Theorem 31.17. Our selection of a particular $\bar{F}$ is not critical, since, as we shall show in Section 49 , any two algebraic closures of $F$ are isomorphic under a map leaving $F$ fixed. From now on in our work, we shall assume that all algebraic extensions and all elements algebraic over a field $F$ under consideration are contained in one fixed algebraic closure $\bar{F}$ of $F$.

Remember that we are engaged in the study of zeros of polynomials. In the terminology of Section 31, studying zeros of polynomials in $F[x]$ amounts to studying the structure of algebraic extensions of $F$ and of elements algebraic over $F$. We shall show that if $E$ is an algebraic extension of $F$ with $\alpha, \beta \in E$, then $\alpha$ and $\beta$ have the same algebraic properties if and only if $\operatorname{irr}(\alpha, F)=\operatorname{irr}(\beta, F)$. We shall phrase this fact in terms of mappings, as we have been doing all along in field theory. We achieve this by showing that if $\operatorname{irr}(\alpha, F)=\operatorname{irr}(\beta, F)$, then there exists an isomorphism $\psi_{\alpha, \beta}$ of $F(\alpha)$ onto $F(\beta)$ that maps each element of $F$ onto itself and maps $\alpha$ onto $\beta$. The next theorem exhibits this isomorphism $\psi_{\alpha, \beta}$. These isomorphisms will become our fundamental tools for the study of algebraic extensions; they supplant the evaluation homomorphisms $\phi_{\alpha}$ of Theorem 22.4, which make their last contribution in defining these isomorphisms. Before stating and proving this theorem, let us introduce some more terminology.[^19]

48.1 Definition Let $E$ be an algebraic extension of a field $F$. Two elements $\alpha, \beta \in E$ are conjugate over $F$ if $\operatorname{irr}(\alpha, F)=\operatorname{irr}(\beta, F)$, that is, if $\alpha$ and $\beta$ are zeros of the same irreducible polynomial over $F$.

48.2 Example The concept of conjugate elements just defined conforms with the classic idea of conjugate complex numbers if we understand that by conjugate complex numbers we mean numbers that are conjugate over $\mathbb{R}$. If $a, b \in \mathbb{R}$ and $b \neq 0$, the conjugate complex numbers $a+b i$ and $a-b i$ are both zeros of $x^{2}-2 a x+a^{2}+b^{2}$, which is irreducible in $\mathbb{R}[x]$.

48.3 Theorem (The Conjugation Isomorphisms) Let $F$ be a field, and let $\alpha$ and $\beta$ be algebraic over $F$ with $\operatorname{deg}(\alpha, F)=n$. The map $\psi_{\alpha, \beta}: F(\alpha) \rightarrow F(\beta)$ defined by

$$
\psi_{\alpha, \beta}\left(c_{0}+c_{i} \alpha+\cdots+c_{n-1} \alpha^{n-1}\right)=c_{0}+c_{1} \beta+\cdots+c_{n-1} \beta^{n-1}
$$

for $c_{i} \in F$ is an isomorphism of $F(\alpha)$ onto $F(\beta)$ if and only if $\alpha$ and $\beta$ are conjugate over $F$.

Proof Suppose that $\psi_{\alpha, \beta}: F(\alpha) \rightarrow F(\beta)$ as defined in the statement of the theorem is an isomorphism. Let $\operatorname{irr}(\alpha, F)=a_{0}+a_{1} x+\cdots+a_{n} x^{n}$. Then $a_{0}+a_{1} \alpha+\cdots+a_{n} \alpha^{n}=0$, so

$$
\psi_{\alpha, \beta}\left(a_{0}+a_{1} \alpha+\cdots+a_{n} \alpha^{n}\right)=a_{0}+a_{1} \beta+\cdots+a_{n} \beta^{n}=0 .
$$

By the last assertion in the statement of Theorem 29.13 this implies that $\operatorname{irr}(\beta, F)$ divides $\operatorname{irr}(\alpha, F)$. A similar argument using the isomorphism $\left(\psi_{\alpha, \beta}\right)^{-1}=\psi_{\beta, \alpha}$ shows that $\operatorname{irr}(\alpha, F)$ divides $\operatorname{irr}(\beta, F)$. Therefore, since both polynomials are monic, $\operatorname{irr}(\alpha, F)=$ $\operatorname{irr}(\beta, F)$, so $\alpha$ and $\beta$ are conjugate over $F$.

Conversely, suppose $\operatorname{irr}(\alpha, F)=\operatorname{irr}(\beta, F)=p(x)$. Then the evaluation homomorphisms $\phi_{\alpha}: F[x] \rightarrow F(\alpha)$ and $\phi_{\beta}: F[x] \rightarrow F(\beta)$ both have the same kernel $\langle p(x)\rangle$. By Theorem 26.17, corresponding to $\phi_{\alpha}: F[x] \rightarrow F(\alpha)$, there is a natural isomorphism $\psi_{\alpha}$ mapping $F[x] /\langle p(x)\rangle$ onto $\phi_{\alpha}[F[x]]=F(\alpha)$. Similarly, $\phi_{\beta}$ gives rise to an isomorphism $\psi_{\beta}$ mapping $F[x] /\langle p(x)\rangle$ onto $F(\beta)$. Let $\psi_{\alpha, \beta}=\psi_{\beta}\left(\psi_{\alpha}\right)^{-1}$. These mappings are diagrammed in Fig. 48.4 where the dashed lines indicate corresponding elements under the mappings. As the composition of two isomorphisms, $\psi_{\alpha, \beta}$ is again an isomorphism and maps $F(\alpha)$ onto $F(\beta)$. For $\left(c_{0}+c_{1} \alpha+\cdots+c_{n-1} \alpha^{n-1}\right) \in F(\alpha)$, we have

$$
\begin{aligned}
& \psi_{\alpha, \beta}\left(c_{0}+c_{1} \alpha+\cdots+c_{n-1} \alpha^{n-1}\right) \\
& \quad=\left(\psi_{\beta} \psi_{\alpha}{ }^{-1}\right)\left(c_{0}+c_{1} \alpha+\cdots+c_{n-1} \alpha^{n-1}\right)
\end{aligned}
$$

