## The Index of a Field Extension

Having discussed the question of existence, we turn now to the question of how many. For a finite extension $E$ of a field $F$, we would like to count how many isomorphisms there are of $E$ onto a subfield of $\bar{F}$ that leave $F$ fixed. We shall show that there are only a finite number of isomorphisms. Since every automorphism in $G(E / F)$ is such an isomorphism, a count of these isomorphisms will include all these automorphisms. Example 48.17 showed that $G(\mathbb{Q}(\sqrt{2}, \sqrt{3}) / \mathbb{Q})$ has four elements, and that $4=[\mathbb{Q}(\sqrt{2}, \sqrt{3}): \mathbb{Q}]$. While such an equality is not always true, it is true in a very important case. The next theorem
takes the first big step in proving this. We state the theorem in more general terms than we shall need, but it does not make the proof any harder.

49.7 Theorem Let $E$ be a finite extension of a field $F$. Let $\sigma$ be an isomorphism of $F$ onto a field $F^{\prime}$, and let $\overline{F^{\prime}}$ be an algebraic closure of $F^{\prime}$. Then the number of extensions of $\sigma$ to an isomorphism $\tau$ of $E$ onto a subfield of $\overline{F^{\prime}}$ is finite, and independent of $F^{\prime}, \overline{F^{\prime}}$, and $\sigma$. That is, the number of extensions is completely determined by the two fields $E$ and $F$; it is intrinsic to them.

Proof The diagram in Fig. 49.8 may help us to follow the construction that we are about to make. This diagram is constructed in the following way. Consider two isomorphisms

$$
\sigma_{1}: F \stackrel{\text { onto }}{\longrightarrow} F_{1}^{\prime}, \quad \sigma_{2}: F \stackrel{\text { onto }}{\longrightarrow} F_{2}^{\prime},
$$

where $\overline{F_{1}^{\prime}}$ and $\overline{F_{2}^{\prime}}$ are algebraic closures of $F_{1}^{\prime}$ and $F_{2}^{\prime}$, respectively. Now $\sigma_{2} \sigma_{1}^{-1}$ is an isomorphism of $F_{1}^{\prime}$ onto $F_{2}^{\prime}$. Then by Theorem 49.3 and Corollary 49.5 there is an isomorphism

$$
\lambda: \overline{F_{1}^{\prime}} \stackrel{\text { onto }}{\longrightarrow} \overline{F_{2}^{\prime}}
$$

extending this isomorphism $\sigma_{2} \sigma_{1}^{-1}: F_{1}^{\prime} \xrightarrow{\text { onto }} F_{2}^{\prime}$. Referring to Fig. 49.8, corresponding to each $\tau_{1}: E \rightarrow \overline{F_{1}^{\prime}}$ that extends $\sigma_{1}$ we obtain an isomorphism $\tau_{2}: E \rightarrow \overline{F_{2}^{\prime}}$, by starting at $E$ and going first to the left, then up, and then to the right. Written algebraically,

$$
\tau_{2}(\alpha)=\left(\lambda \tau_{1}\right)(\alpha)
$$

for $\alpha \in E$. Clearly $\tau_{2}$ extends $\sigma_{2}$. The fact that we could have started with $\tau_{2}$ and recovered $\tau_{1}$ by defining

$$
\tau_{1}(\alpha)=\left(\lambda^{-1} \tau_{2}\right)(\alpha)
$$

that is, by chasing the other way around the diagram, shows that the correspondence between $\tau_{1}: E \rightarrow \overline{F_{1}^{\prime}}$ and $\tau_{2}: E \rightarrow \overline{F_{2}^{\prime}}$ is one to one. In view of this one-to-one correspondence, the number of $\tau$ extending $\sigma$ is independent of $F^{\prime}, \overline{F^{\prime}}$ and $\sigma$.

That the number of mappings extending $\sigma$ is finite follows from the fact that since $E$ is a finite extension of $F, E=F\left(\alpha_{1}, \cdots, \alpha_{n}\right)$ for some $\alpha_{1}, \cdots, \alpha_{n}$ in $E$, by Theorem 31.11.

![](https://cdn.mathpix.com/cropped/2024_01_27_9289ad7bed1dd2e5e553g-398.jpg?height=350&width=610&top_left_y=1966&top_left_x=953)

49.8 Figure

There are only a finite number of possible candiates for the images $\tau\left(\alpha_{i}\right)$ in $\overline{F^{\prime}}$, for if

$$
\operatorname{irr}\left(\alpha_{i}, F\right)=a_{i 0}+a_{i 1} x+\cdots+a_{i m_{i}} x^{m_{i}}
$$

where $a_{i k} \in F$, then $\tau\left(\alpha_{i}\right)$ must be one of the zeros in $\overline{F^{\prime}}$ of

$$
\left[\sigma\left(a_{i 0}\right)+\sigma\left(a_{i 1}\right) x+\cdots+\sigma\left(a_{i m_{i}}\right) x^{m_{i}}\right] \in F^{\prime}[x] .
$$

49.9 Definition Let $E$ be a finite extension of a field $F$. The number of isomorphisms of $E$ onto a subfield of $\bar{F}$ leaving $F$ fixed is the index $\{E: F\}$ of $E$ over $F$.

49.10 Corollary If $F \leq E \leq K$, where $K$ is a finite extension field of the field $F$, then $\{K: F\}=$ $\{K: E\}\{E: F\}$.

Proof It follows from Theorem 49.7 that each of the $\{E: F\}$ isomorphisms $\tau_{i}$ of $E$ onto a subfield of $\bar{F}$ leaving $F$ fixed has $\{K: E\}$ extensions to an isomorphism of $K$ onto a subfield of $\bar{F}$.

The preceding corollary was really the main thing we were after. Note that it counts something. Never underestimate a result that counts something, even if it is only called a "corollary."

We shall show in Section 51 that unless $F$ is an infinite field of characteristics $p \neq 0$, we always have $[E: F]=\{E: F\}$ for every finite extension field $E$ of $F$. For the case $E=F(\alpha)$, the $\{F(\alpha): F\}$ extensions of the identity map $\iota: F \rightarrow F$ to maps of $F(\alpha)$ onto a subfield of $\bar{F}$ are given by the conjugation isomorphisms $\psi_{\alpha, \beta}$ for each conjugate $\beta$ in $\bar{F}$ of $\alpha$ over $F$. Thus if $\operatorname{irr}(\alpha, F)$ has $n$ distinct zeros in $\bar{F}$, we have $\{E: F\}=n$. We shall show later that unless $F$ is infinite and of characteristic $p \neq 0$, the number of distinct zeros of $\operatorname{irr}(\alpha, F)$ is $\operatorname{deg}(\alpha, F)=[F(\alpha): F]$.

49.11 Example $\quad$ Consider $E=\mathbb{Q}(\sqrt{2}, \sqrt{3})$ over $\mathbb{Q}$, as in Example 48.17. Our work in that example shows that $\{E: \mathbb{Q}\}=[E: \mathbb{Q}]=4$. Also, $\{E: \mathbb{Q}(\sqrt{2})\}=2$, and $\{\mathbb{Q}(\sqrt{2}): \mathbb{Q}\}=2$, so

$$
4=\{E: \mathbb{Q}\}=\{E: \mathbb{Q}(\sqrt{2})\}\{\mathbb{Q}(\sqrt{2}): \mathbb{Q}\}=(2)(2)
$$

This illustrates Corollary 49.10

## Proof of the Extension Theorem

We restate the Isomorphism Extension Theorem 49.3.

Isomorphism Extension Theorem Let $E$ be an algebraic extension of a field $F$. Let $\sigma$ be an isomorphism of $F$ onto a field $F^{\prime}$. Let $\overline{F^{\prime}}$ be an algebraic closure of $F^{\prime}$. Then $\sigma$ can be extended to an isomorphism $\tau$ of $E$ onto a subfield of $\overline{F^{\prime}}$ such that $\tau(a)=\sigma(a)$ for $a \in F$.

Proof Consider all pairs $(L, \lambda)$, where $L$ is a field such that $F \leq L \leq E$ and $\lambda$ is an isomorphism of $L$ onto a subfield of $\overline{F^{\prime}}$ such that $\lambda(a)=\sigma(a)$ for $a \in F$. The set $S$ of such
pairs $(L, \lambda)$ is nonempty, since $(F, \sigma)$ is such a pair. Define a partial ordering on $S$ by $\left(L_{1}, \lambda_{1}\right) \leq\left(L_{2}, \lambda_{2}\right)$, if $L_{1} \leq L_{2}$ and $\lambda_{1}(a)=\lambda_{2}(a)$ for $a \in L_{1}$. It is readily checked that this relation $\leq$ does give a partial ordering of $S$.

Let $T=\left\{\left(H_{i}, \lambda_{i}\right) \mid i \in I\right\}$ be a chain of $S$. We claim that $H=\bigcup_{i \in I} H_{i}$ is a subfield of $E$. Let $a, b \in H$, where $a \in H_{1}$ and $b \in H_{2}$; then either $H_{1} \leq H_{2}$ or $H_{2} \leq H_{1}$, since $T$ is a chain. If, say, $H_{1} \leq H_{2}$, then $a, b, \in H_{2}$, so $a \pm b, a b$, and $a / b$ for $b \neq 0$ are all in $H_{2}$ and hence in $H$. Since for each $i \in I, F \subseteq H_{i} \subseteq E$, we have $F \subseteq H \subseteq E$. Thus $H$ is a subfield of $E$.

Define $\lambda: H \rightarrow \overline{F^{\prime}}$ as follows. Let $c \in H$. Then $c \in H_{i}$ for some $i \in I$, and let

$$
\lambda(c)=\lambda_{i}(c)
$$

The map $\lambda$ is well defined because if $c \in H_{1}$ and $c \in H_{2}$, then either $\left(H_{1}, \lambda_{1}\right) \leq\left(H_{2}, \lambda_{2}\right)$ or $\left(H_{2}, \lambda_{2}\right) \leq\left(H_{1}, \lambda_{1}\right)$, since $T$ is a chain. In either case, $\lambda_{1}(c)=\lambda_{2}(c)$. We claim that $\lambda$ is an isomorphism of $H$ onto a subfield of $\overline{F^{\prime}}$. If $a, b \in H$ then there is an $H_{i}$ such that $a, b \in H_{i}$, and

$$
\lambda(a+b)=\lambda_{i}(a+b)=\lambda_{i}(a)+\lambda_{i}(b)=\lambda(a)+\lambda(b)
$$

Similarly,

$$
\lambda(a b)=\lambda_{i}(a b)=\lambda_{i}(a) \lambda_{i}(b)=\lambda(a) \lambda(b) .
$$

If $\lambda(a)=0$, then $a \in H_{i}$ for some $i$ implies that $\lambda_{i}(a)=0$, so $a=0$. Therefore, $\lambda$ is an isomorphism. Thus $(H, \lambda) \in S$, and it is clear from our definitions of $H$ and $\lambda$ that $(H, \lambda)$ is an upper bound for $T$.

We have shown that every chain of $S$ has an upper bound in $S$, so the hypotheses of Zorn's lemma are satisfied. Hence there exists a maximal element $(K, \tau)$ of $S$. Let $\tau(K)=K^{\prime}$, where $K^{\prime} \leq \overline{F^{\prime}}$. Now if $K \neq E$, let $\alpha \in E$ but $\alpha \notin K$. Now $\alpha$ is algebraic over $F$, so $\alpha$ is algebraic over $K$. Also, let $p(x)=\operatorname{irr}(\alpha, K)$. Let $\psi_{\alpha}$ be the canonical isomorphism

$$
\psi_{\alpha}: K[x] /\langle p(x)\rangle \rightarrow K(\alpha)
$$

corresponding to the evaluation homomorphism $\phi_{\alpha}: K[x] \rightarrow K(\alpha)$. If

$$
p(x)=a_{0}+a_{1} x+\cdots+a_{n} x^{n}
$$

consider

$$
q(x)=\tau\left(a_{0}\right)+\tau\left(a_{1}\right) x+\cdots+\tau\left(a_{n}\right) x^{n}
$$

in $K^{\prime}[x]$. Since $\tau$ is an isomorphism, $q(x)$ is irreducible in $K^{\prime}[x]$. Since $K^{\prime} \leq \overline{F^{\prime}}$, there is a zero $\alpha^{\prime}$ of $q(x)$ in $\overline{F^{\prime}}$. Let

$$
\psi_{\alpha^{\prime}}: K^{\prime}[x] /\langle q(x)\rangle \rightarrow K^{\prime}\left(\alpha^{\prime}\right)
$$

![](https://cdn.mathpix.com/cropped/2024_01_27_9289ad7bed1dd2e5e553g-401.jpg?height=287&width=1084&top_left_y=461&top_left_x=648)

49.12 Figure

be the isomorphism analogous to $\psi_{\alpha}$. Finally, let

$$
\bar{\tau}: K[x] /\langle p(x)\rangle \rightarrow K^{\prime}[x] /\langle q(x)\rangle
$$

be the isomorphism extending $\tau$ on $K$ and mapping $x+\langle p(x)\rangle$ onto $x+\langle q(x)\rangle$. (See Fig. 49.12.) Then the composition of maps

$$
\psi_{\alpha^{\prime}} \bar{\tau} \psi_{\alpha}^{-1}: K(\alpha) \rightarrow K^{\prime}\left(\alpha^{\prime}\right)
$$

is an isomorphism of $K(\alpha)$ onto a subfield of $\overline{F^{\prime}}$. Clearly, $(K, \tau)<\left(K(\alpha), \psi_{\alpha^{\prime}} \bar{\tau} \psi_{\alpha}^{-1}\right)$, which contradicts that $(K, \tau)$ is maximal. Therefore we must have had $K=E$.

