## Section 51 Separable Extensions

## Multiplicity of Zeros of a Polynomial

Remember that we are now always assuming that all algebraic extensions of a field $F$ under consideration are contained in one fixed algebraic closure $\bar{F}$ of $F$.

Our next aim is to determine, for a finite extension $E$ of $F$, under what conditions $\{E: F\}=[E: F]$. The key to answering this question is to consider the multiplicity of zeros of polynomials.

51.1 Definition Let $f(x) \in F[x]$. An element $\alpha$ of $\bar{F}$ such that $f(\alpha)=0$ is a zero of $f(x)$ of multiplicity $v$ if $v$ is the greatest integer such that $(x-\alpha)^{v}$ is a factor of $f(x)$ in $\bar{F}[x]$.

The next theorem shows that the multiplicities of the zeros of one given irreducible polynomial over a field are all the same. The ease with which we can prove this theorem is a further indication of the power of our conjugation isomorphisms and of our whole approach to the study of zeros of polynomials by means of mappings.

51.2 Theorem Let $f(x)$ be irreducible in $F[x]$. Then all zeros of $f(x)$ in $\bar{F}$ have the same multiplicity.

Proof Let $\alpha$ and $\beta$ be zeros of $f(x)$ in $\bar{F}$. Then by Theorem 48.3, there is a conjugation isomorphism $\psi_{\alpha, \beta}: F(\alpha) \xrightarrow{\text { onto }} F(\beta)$. By Corollary $49.4, \psi_{\alpha, \beta}$ can be extended to an isomorphism $\tau: \bar{F} \rightarrow \bar{F}$. Then $\tau$ induces a natural isomorphism $\tau_{x}: \bar{F}[x] \rightarrow \bar{F}[x]$, with $\tau_{x}(x)=x$. Now $\tau_{x}$ leaves $f(x)$ fixed, since $f(x) \in F[x]$ and $\psi_{\alpha, \beta}$ leaves $F$ fixed. However,

$$
\tau_{x}\left((x-\alpha)^{v}\right)=(x-\beta)^{v},
$$

which shows that the multiplicity of $\beta$ in $f(x)$ is greater than or equal to the multiplicity of $\alpha$. A symmetric argument gives the reverse inequality, so the multiplicity of $\alpha$ equals that of $\beta$.

51.3 Corollary If $f(x)$ is irreducible in $F[x]$, then $f(x)$ has a factorization in $\bar{F}[x]$ of the form

$$
a \prod_{i}\left(x-\alpha_{i}\right)^{v}
$$

where the $\alpha_{i}$ are the distinct zeros of $f(x)$ in $\bar{F}$ and $a \in F$.

Proof The corollary is immediate from Theorem 51.2.

At this point, we should probably show by an example that the phenomenon of a zero of multiplicity greater than 1 of an irreducible polynomial can occur. We shall show later in this section that it can only occur for a polynomial over an infinite field of characteristic $p \neq 0$.

51.4 Example Let $E=\mathbb{Z}_{p}(y)$, where $y$ is an indeterminate. Let $t=y^{p}$, and let $F$ be the subfield $\mathbb{Z}_{p}(t)$ of $E$. (See Fig. 51.5.) Now $E=F(y)$ is algebraic over $F$, for $y$ is a zero of $\left(x^{p}-t\right) \in F[x]$. By Theorem 29.13, $\operatorname{irr}(y, F)$ must divide $x^{p}-t$ in $F[x]$. [Actually, $\operatorname{irr}(y, F)=x^{p}-t$. We leave a proof of this to the exercises (see Exercise 10).] Since $F(y)$ is not equal to $F$, we must have the degree of $\operatorname{irr}(y, F) \geq 2$. But note that

![](https://cdn.mathpix.com/cropped/2024_01_27_9289ad7bed1dd2e5e553g-408.jpg?height=390&width=230&top_left_y=1708&top_left_x=362)

51.5 Figure

$$
x^{p}-t=x^{p}-y^{p}=(x-y)^{p} \text {, }
$$

since $E$ has characteristic $p$ (see Theorem 48.19 and the following comment). Thus $y$ is a zero of $\operatorname{irr}(y, F)$ of multiplicity $>1$. Actually, $x^{p}-t=\operatorname{irr}(y, F)$, so the multiplicity of $y$ is $p$.

From here on we rely heavily on Theorem 49.7 and its corollary. Theorem 48.3 and its corollary show that for a simple algebraic extension $F(\alpha)$ of $F$ there is one extension of the identity isomorphism $\iota$ mapping $F$ into $F$ for every distinct zero of $\operatorname{irr}(\alpha, F)$ and that these are the only extensions of $\iota$. Thus $\{F(\alpha): F\}$ is the number of distinct zeros of $\operatorname{irr}(\alpha, F)$.

In view of our work with the theorem of Lagrange and Theorem 31.4, we should recognize the potential of a theorem like this next one.

51.6 Theorem If $E$ is a finite extension of $F$, then $\{E: F\}$ divides $[E: F]$.

Proof By Theorem 31.11, if $E$ is finite over $F$, then $E=F\left(\alpha_{1}, \cdots, \alpha_{n}\right)$, where $\alpha_{i} \in \bar{F}$. Let $\operatorname{irr}\left(\alpha_{i}, F\left(\alpha_{1}, \cdots, \alpha_{i-1}\right)\right)$ have $\alpha_{i}$ as one of $n_{i}$ distinct zeros that are all of a common multiplicity $v_{i}$, by Theorem 51.2. Then

$$
\left[F\left(\alpha_{1}, \cdots, \alpha_{i}\right): F\left(\alpha_{1}, \cdots, \alpha_{i-1}\right)\right]=n_{i} v_{i}=\left\{F\left(\alpha_{1}, \cdots, \alpha_{i}\right): F\left(\alpha_{1}, \cdots, \alpha_{i-1}\right)\right\} v_{i}
$$

By Theorem 31.4 and Corollary 49.10,

$$
[E: F]=\prod_{i} n_{i} v_{i}
$$

and

$$
\{E: F\}=\prod_{i} n_{i} .
$$

Therefore, $\{E: F\}$ divides $[E: F]$.

## Separable Extensions

51.7 Definition A finite extension $E$ of $F$ is a separable extension of $F$ if $\{E: F\}=[E: F]$. An element $\alpha$ of $\bar{F}$ is separable over $F$ if $F(\alpha)$ is a separable extension of $F$. An irreducible polynomial $f(x) \in F[x]$ is separable over $F$ if every zero of $f(x)$ in $\bar{F}$ is separable over $F$.

51.8 Example The field $E=\mathbb{Q}[\sqrt{2}, \sqrt{3}]$ is separable over $\mathbb{Q}$ since we saw in Example 50.8 that $\{E: \mathbb{Q}\}=4=[E: \mathbb{Q}]$.

To make things a little easier, we have restricted our definition of a separable extension of a field $F$ to finite extensions $E$ of $F$. For the corresponding definition for infinite extensions, see Exercise 12.

We know that $\{F(\alpha): F\}$ is the number of distinct zeros of $\operatorname{irr}(\alpha, F)$. Also, the multiplicity of $\alpha \operatorname{in} \operatorname{irr}(\alpha, F)$ is the same as the multiplicity of each conjugate of $\alpha$ over $F$, by Theorem 51.2. Thus $\alpha$ is separable over $F$ if and only if $\operatorname{irr}(\alpha, F)$ has all zeros of multiplicity 1. This tells us at once that an irreducible polynomial $f(x) \in F[x]$ is separable over $F$ if and only if $f(x)$ has all zeros of multiplicity 1.

51.9 Theorem If $K$ is a finite extension of $E$ and $E$ is a finite extension of $F$, that is, $F \leq E \leq K$, then $K$ is separable over $F$ if and only if $K$ is separable over $E$ and $E$ is separable over $F$.

Proof Now

$$
[K: F]=[K: E][E: F],
$$

and

$$
\{K: F\}=\{K: E\}\{E: F\} .
$$

Then if $K$ is separable over $F$, so that $[K: F]=\{K: F\}$, we must have $[K: E]=$ $\{K: E\}$ and $[E: F]=\{E: F\}$, since in each case the index divides the degree, by Theorem 51.6. Thus, if $K$ is separable over $F$, then $K$ is separable over $E$ and $E$ is separable over $F$.

For the converse, note that $[K: E]=\{K: E\}$ and $[E: F]=\{E: F\}$ imply that

$$
[K: F]=[K: E][E: F]=\{K: E\}\{E: F\}=\{K: F\} .
$$

Theorem 51.9 can be extended in the obvious way, by induction, to any finite tower of finite extensions. The top field is a separable extension of the bottom one if and only if each field is a separable extension of the one immediately under it.

51.10 Corollary If $E$ is a finite extension of $F$, then $E$ is separable over $F$ if and only if each $\alpha$ in $E$ is separable over $F$.

Proof Suppose that $E$ is separable over $F$, and let $\alpha \in E$. Then

$$
F \leq F(\alpha) \leq E
$$

and Theorem 51.9 shows that $F(\alpha)$ is separable over $F$.

Suppose, conversely, that every $\alpha \in E$ is separable over $F$. Since $E$ is a finite extension of $F$, there exist $\alpha_{1}, \cdots, \alpha_{n}$ such that

$$
F<F\left(\alpha_{1}\right)<F\left(\alpha_{1}, \alpha_{2}\right)<\cdots<E=F\left(\alpha_{1}, \cdots, \alpha_{n}\right) .
$$

Now since $\alpha_{i}$ is separable over $F, \alpha_{i}$ is separable over $F\left(\alpha_{1}, \cdots, \alpha_{i-1}\right)$, because

$$
q(x)=\operatorname{irr}\left(\alpha_{i}, F\left(\alpha_{1}, \cdots, \alpha_{i-1}\right)\right)
$$

divides $\operatorname{irr}\left(\alpha_{i}, F\right)$, so that $\alpha_{i}$ is a zero of $q(x)$ of multiplicity 1 . Thus $F\left(\alpha_{1}, \cdots, \alpha_{i}\right)$ is separable over $F\left(\alpha_{1}, \cdots, \alpha_{i-1}\right)$, so $E$ is separable over $F$ by Theorem 51.9 , extended by induction.

## Perfect Fields

We now turn to the task of proving that $\alpha$ can fail to be separable over $F$ only if $F$ is an infinite field of characteristic $p \neq 0$. One method is to introduce formal derivatives of polynomials. While this is an elegant technique, and also a useful one, we shall, for the sake of brevity, use the following lemma instead. Formal derivatives are developed in Exercises 15 through 22.

51.11 Lemma Let $\bar{F}$ be an algebraic closure of $F$, and let

$$
f(x)=x^{n}+a_{n-1} x^{n-1}+\cdots+a_{1} x+a_{0}
$$

be any monic polynomial in $\bar{F}[x]$. If $(f(x))^{m} \in F[x]$ and $m \cdot 1 \neq 0$ in $F$, then $f(x) \in$ $F[x]$, that is, all $a_{i} \in F$.

Proof We must show that $a_{i} \in F$, and we proceed, by induction on $r$, to show that $a_{n-r} \in F$. For $r=1$,

$$
(f(x))^{m}=x^{m n}+(m \cdot 1) a_{n-1} x^{m n-1}+\cdots+a_{0}{ }^{m} .
$$

## Part X Automorphisms and Galois Theory

Since $(f(x))^{m} \in F[x]$, we have, in particular,

$$
(m \cdot 1) a_{n-1} \in F
$$

Thus $a_{n-1} \in F$, since $m \cdot 1 \neq 0$ in $F$.

As induction hypothesis, suppose that $a_{n-r} \in F$ for $r=1,2, \cdots, k$. Then the coefficient of $x^{m n-(k+1)}$ in $(f(x))^{m}$ is of the form

$$
(m \cdot 1) a_{n-(k+1)}+g_{k+1}\left(a_{n-1}, a_{n-2}, \cdots, a_{n-k}\right),
$$

where $g_{k+1}\left(a_{n-1}, a_{n-2}, \cdots, a_{n-k}\right)$ is a formal polynomial expression in $a_{n-1}, a_{n-2}, \cdots$, $a_{n-k}$. By the induction hypothesis that we just stated, $g_{k+1}\left(a_{n-1}, a_{n-2}, \cdots, a_{n-k}\right) \in F$, so $a_{n-(k+1)} \in F$, since $m \cdot 1 \neq 0$ in $F$.

We are now in a position to handle fields $F$ of characteristic zero and to show that for a finite extension $E$ of $F$, we have $\{E: F\}=[E: F]$. By definition, this amounts to proving that every finite extension of a field of characteristic zero is a separable extension. First, we give a definition.

51.12 Definition A field is perfect if every finite extension is a separable extension.

51.13 Theorem Every field of characteristic zero is perfect.

Proof Let $E$ be a finite extension of a field $F$ of characteristic zero, and let $\alpha \in E$. Then $f(x)=\operatorname{irr}(\alpha, F)$ factors in $\bar{F}[x]$ into $\prod_{i}\left(x-\alpha_{i}\right)^{\nu}$, where the $\alpha_{i}$ are the distinct zeros of $\operatorname{irr}(\alpha, F)$, and, say, $\alpha=\alpha_{1}$. Thus

$$
f(x)=\left(\prod_{i}\left(x-\alpha_{i}\right)\right)^{v}
$$

and since $v \cdot 1 \neq 0$ for a field $F$ of characteristic 0 , we must have

$$
\left(\prod_{i}\left(x-\alpha_{i}\right)\right) \in F[x]
$$

by Lemma 51.11. Since $f(x)$ is irreducible and of minimal degree in $F[x]$ having $\alpha$ as a zero, we then see that $v=1$. Therefore, $\alpha$ is separable over $F$ for all $\alpha \in E$. By Corollary 51.10 , this means that $E$ is a separable extension of $F$.

Lemma 51.11 will also get us through for the case of a finite field, although the proof is a bit harder.

51.14 Theorem Every finite field is perfect.

Proof Let $F$ be a finite field of characteristic $p$, and let $E$ be a finite extension of $F$. Let $\alpha \in E$. We need to show that $\alpha$ is separable over $F$. Now $f(x)=\operatorname{irr}(\alpha, F)$ factors in $\bar{F}$ into $\prod_{i}\left(x-\alpha_{i}\right)^{v}$, where the $\alpha_{i}$ are the distinct zeros of $f(x)$, and, say, $\alpha=\alpha_{1}$. Let $v=p^{t} e$,
where $p$ does not divide $e$. Then

$$
f(x)=\prod_{i}\left(x-\alpha_{i}\right)^{v}=\left(\prod_{i}\left(x-\alpha_{i}\right)^{p^{t}}\right)^{e}
$$

is in $F[x]$, and by Lemma $51.11, \prod_{i}\left(x-\alpha_{i}\right)^{p^{t}}$ is in $F[x]$ since $e \cdot 1 \neq 0$ in $F$. Since $f(x)=\operatorname{irr}(\alpha, F)$ is of minimal degree over $F$ having $\alpha$ as a zero, we must have $e=1$.

Theorem 48.19 and the remark following it show then that

$$
f(x)=\prod_{i}\left(x-\alpha_{i}\right)^{p^{t}}=\prod_{i}\left(x^{p^{t}}-\alpha_{i}^{p^{t}}\right) .
$$

Thus, if we regard $f(x)$ as $g\left(x^{p^{t}}\right)$, we must have $g(x) \in F[x]$. Now $g(x)$ is separable over $F$ with distinct zeros $\alpha_{i}^{p^{t}}$. Consider $F\left(\alpha_{1}^{p^{t}}\right)=F\left(\alpha^{p^{t}}\right)$. Then $F\left(\alpha^{p^{t}}\right)$ is separable over $F$. Since $x^{p^{t}}-\alpha^{p^{t}}=(x-\alpha)^{p^{t}}$, we see that $\alpha$ is the only zero of $x^{p^{t}}-\alpha^{p^{t}}$ in $\bar{F}$. As a finite-dimensional vector space over a finite field $F, F\left(\alpha^{p^{t}}\right)$ must be again a finite field. Hence the map

$$
\sigma_{p}: F\left(\alpha^{p^{t}}\right) \rightarrow F\left(\alpha^{p^{t}}\right)
$$

given by $\sigma_{p}(a)=a^{p}$ for $a \in F\left(\alpha^{p^{t}}\right)$ is an automorphism of $F\left(\alpha^{p^{t}}\right)$ by Theorem 48.19. Consequently, $\left(\sigma_{p}\right)^{t}$ is also an automorphism of $F\left(\alpha^{p^{t}}\right)$, and

$$
\left(\sigma_{p}\right)^{t}(a)=a^{p^{t}}
$$

Since an automorphism of $F\left(\alpha^{p^{t}}\right)$ is an onto map, there is $\beta \in F\left(\alpha^{p^{t}}\right)$ such that $\left(\sigma_{p}\right)^{t}(\beta)=\alpha^{p^{t}}$. But then $\beta^{p^{t}}=\alpha^{p^{t}}$, and we saw that $\alpha$ was the only zero of $x^{p^{t}}-\alpha^{p^{t}}$, so we must have $\beta=\alpha$. Since $\beta \in F\left(\alpha^{p^{t}}\right)$, we have $F(\alpha)=F\left(\alpha^{p^{t}}\right)$. Since $F\left(\alpha^{p^{t}}\right)$ was separable over $F$, we now see that $F(\alpha)$ is separable over $F$. Therefore, $\alpha$ is separable over $F$ and $t=0$.

We have shown that for $\alpha \in E, \alpha$ is separable over $F$. Then by Corollary $51.10, E$ is a separable extension of $F$.

We have completed our aim, which was to show that fields of characteristic 0 and finite fields have only separable finite extensions, that is, these fields are perfect. For finite extensions $E$ of such perfect fields $F$, we then have $[E: F]=\{E: F\}$.

## The Primitive Element Theorem

The following theorem is a classic of field theory.

51.15 Theorem

(Primitive Element Theorem) Let $E$ be a finite separable extension of a field $F$. Then there exists $\alpha \in E$ such that $E=F(\alpha)$. (Such an element $\alpha$ is a primitive element.) That is, a finite separable extension of a field is a simple extension.

Proof If $F$ is a finite field, then $E$ is also finite. Let $\alpha$ be a generator for the cylic group $E^{*}$ of nonzero elements of $E$ under multiplication. (See Theorem 33.5.) Clearly, $E=F(\alpha)$, so $\alpha$ is a primitive element in this case.

## Part X Automorphisms and Galois Theory

We now assume that $F$ is infinite, and prove our theorem in the case that $E=$ $F(\beta, \gamma)$. The induction argument from this to the general case is straightforward. Let $\operatorname{irr}(\beta, F)$ have distinct zeros $\beta=\beta_{1}, \cdots, \beta_{n}$, and let $\operatorname{irr}(\gamma, F)$ have distinct zeros $\gamma=$ $\gamma_{1}, \cdots, \gamma_{m}$ in $\bar{F}$, where all zeros are of multiplicity 1 , since $E$ is a separable extension of $F$. Since $F$ is infinite, we can find $a \in F$ such that

$$
a \neq\left(\beta_{i}-\beta\right) /\left(\gamma-\gamma_{j}\right)
$$

for all $i$ and $j$, with $j \neq 1$. That is, $a\left(\gamma-\gamma_{j}\right) \neq \beta_{i}-\beta$. Letting $\alpha=\beta+a \gamma$, we have $\alpha=\beta+a \gamma \neq \beta_{i}+a \gamma_{j}$, so

$$
\alpha-a \gamma_{j} \neq \beta_{i}
$$

for all $i$ and all $j \neq 1$. Let $f(x)=\operatorname{irr}(\beta, F)$, and consider

$$
h(x)=f(\alpha-a x) \in(F(\alpha))[x] .
$$

Now $h(\gamma)=f(\beta)=0$. However, $h\left(\gamma_{j}\right) \neq 0$ for $j \neq 1$ by construction, since the $\beta_{i}$ were the only zeros of $f(x)$. Hence $h(x)$ and $g(x)=\operatorname{irr}(\gamma, F)$ have a common factor in $(F(\alpha))[x]$, namely $\operatorname{irr}(\gamma, F(\alpha))$, which must be linear, since $\gamma$ is the only common zero of $g(x)$ and $h(x)$. Thus $\gamma \in F(\alpha)$, and therefore $\beta=\alpha-a \gamma$ is in $F(\alpha)$. Hence $F(\beta, \gamma)=F(\alpha)$.

51.16 Corollary A finite extension of a field of characteristic zero is a simple extension.

Proof This corollary follows at once from Theorems 51.13 and 51.15.

We see that the only possible "bad case" where a finite extension may not be simple is a finite extension of an infinite field of characteristic $p \neq 0$.

